<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats bolstered their huge redistricting
advantage by adding two big prizes - Florida and Texas - to the
list of states where they hold a lock on redrawing political lines
for the next decade.
   Besides taking the governorships in those two states -
considered key because together they stand to gain seven U.S. House
seats - Democrats added Rhode Island, Oklahoma and New Mexico to
their remapping monopolies on Tuesday.
   Republicans won a crucial redistricting battle by taking the
California governor's race. The GOP needed it to keep a role in
drawing lines for the seven new House seats California is expected
to gain, because Democrats easily retained control of the
Legislature.
   The GOP also scored victories by winning the Ohio and Illinois
governorships, but Democrats clearly will have the national edge on
the process of reapportioning the 19 House seats that will change
hands due to population shifts of the 1980s.
   Advantages won Tuesday should help cement Democrats as the House
majority party for at least another decade. Democrats also said the
Florida and Texas wins would boost their 1992 presidential hopes.
   ``We feel better about the prospects of fair districts when the
pen is in Democratic hands,'' said Paul Tully, political director
for the Democratic National Committee.
   ``These are not only net victories but victories in places that
because of their population growth will grow more important to the
future of this country and also to the presidential race,'' Tully
said.
   According to preliminary Census Bureau figures, eight states
will gain and 13 will lose seats when House districts are
reapportioned next year. Democrats will control the process
outright in at least five of the states gaining House seats.
   Despite the anti-incumbent mood thought to be sweeping the
country, voters appeared unwilling to turn out their state
legislators. Millions of dollars were spent on legislative races
this year due to their importance in the redistricting picture, but
few chambers changed hands.
   The GOP turned back Democratic efforts to take over the senates
of New York, Pennsylvania and Ohio. Redistricting power will be
shared in all three states, which will lose House seats in 1992.
   ``This proves the Republican Party is alive and well despite the
doom and gloom predicted,'' said New York's state Senate Republican
leader, Ralph Marino.
   Democrats fended off Republican efforts to take over the state
senates in Illinois and Florida and the lower chamber in
Pennsylvania. The GOP was trying to wrest control of the Oregon
House from Democrats, too.
   Arizona's gubernatorial race was up for grabs, as the lead
seesawed throughout Election Night.
   Meanwhile, the GOP lost the Indiana House, but Republicans kept
control of the state Senate. Democrats captured control of the
state Senate in Arizona. A Democratic effort to gain control of the
Washington state Senate hinged on absentee ballots in two
neck-and-neck races.
   In Michigan, Republicans kept control of the state Senate.
   By losing in the governorships in Texas and Florida, the GOP
lost its say in how political maps will be drawn for those ne
House seats.
   Similar gubernatorial wins in Rhode Island, Oklahoma and New
Mexico gave Democrats absolute control there, too. The House
delegations in those states won't change, but Democrats can aim to
draw districts that protect their House incumbents and perhaps
endanger GOP lawmakers. The political lines for state seats are at
stake as well.
   Another victory for Democrats came in Kansas, where they ousted
a Republican governor and gained control of the state House. Kansas
will lose one House seat.
   Election Day began with Democrats controlling 69 of the nation's
99 legislative chambers, and that margin was on track to change
little.
   More than 6,100 legislative races were decided across the
country, but the focus of national party organizations was about 50
races in 10 states in which chambers were held by narrow
majorities.
   The Democrats were in position to draw districts that in 1992
could pad their House majority, now at 258-175 with two vacancies,
by a dozen seats or more beyoe Tuesday.
   The other five House seats are expected to go to Virginia, North
Carolina, Georgia, Washington and Arizona. Democrats already had a
redistricting monopoly in Virginia and kept their sole control in
North Carolina and Georgia. A nonpartisnd the gains madan commission draws
the map
in Washington.
   Among the 13 states losing seats, New York will suffer the most
- giving up three.
   Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan and Illinois are to lose two seats
each. Losing one will be Massachusetts, New Jersey, West Virginia,
Kentucky, Louisiana, Iowa, Kansas and Montana.
