<HEAD>Democrats Post Impressive Gains In Redistricting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6 and 9 to show GOP winning governor's races in
Vermont and Illinois, bgng.: The Ohio</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats on Tuesday padded their overwhelming
control of political redistricting, plucking the potent Florida and
Texas governorships from GOP hands and adding Rhode Island,
Oklahoma and New Mexico to their remapping monopolies.
   The Florida and Texas defeats were disastrous for Republicans,
and Democrats were in the running for the only remaining major GOP
redistricting weapon - the California governorship.
   Democrats clearly will have a huge edge when lines are drawn for
1992 congressional races, all but cementing the Republicans as the
House minority for another decade and perhaps far longer. And
Democrats were calling the Texas and Florida victories a boost for
their 1992 presidential hopes.
   ``We feel better about the prospects of fair districts when the
pen is in Democratic hands,'' said Democratic National Committee
political director Paul Tully. ``These are not only net victories
but victories in places that because of their population growth
will grow more important to the future of this country and also to
the presidential race.''
   In all, eight states will gain and 13 will lose seats when House
districts are reapportioned to reflect population shifts of the
1980s, according to preliminary census data. Democrats will control
the process outright in at least five of the states gaining House
seats.
   The Ohio governorship was the only significant redistricting
victory for Republicans as results from gubernatorial and
legislative races trickled in. So frustrating was the GOP's night
that the only redistricting monopoly the GOP gained was in Vermont
- which has only one House seat anyway.
   Despite the millions spent on oft-ignored state races with the
post-Census redistricting in mind, it appeared but a few of the
dozen targeted chambers would change hands.
   The GOP turned back Democratic efforts to take over the New
York, Pennsylvania and Ohio Senates. Redistricting power in all
three states, which will lose House seats in 1992, will be shared.
   Republicans failed in their bid to wrest the Illinois Senate
from Democrats but won a close governor's race to keep a say in
redistricting there. The GOP was trailing in bids to win over the
Democratic Florida Senate and Pennsylvania House. Early returns
showed control of the Oregon House within reach.
   The Indiana House was likely to go from GOP hands to the
Democrats. Other Democratic targets were the state senates in
Indiana, Michigan and Washington and both chambers in Arizona.
   The GOP suffered a big loss when Democrat Lawton Chiles unseated
Florida's Republican governor, and things would only get worse.
   The Rhode Island, Oklahoma and New Mexico governor's offices
went from Republican to Democratic hands and then Texas was seized
by the Democrats too.
   Democrats now will have sole power over the remapping in those
states. Florida is likely to gain four House seats and Texas three.
The House delegations in Rhode Island, Oklahoma and New Mexico
won't change, but control of redistricting should allow Democrats
to draw districts that protect their House incumbents and perhaps
endanger GOP lawmakers.
   Another victory for Democrats came in Kansas, where by unseating
a Republican governor the party went from being shut out of the
process to having veto power in redistricting. Kansas will lose one
House seat.
   The Republicans' last hope was California, which will get seven
of the 19 shifting seats. But even with a win in the governor's
race there the GOP would only share the power with the Democratic
legislature.
   Democrats, with huge majorities in many legislative chambers,
were virtually assured a redistricting voice in all the
battleground states even before the polls opened Tuesday.
   The day began with Democrats controlling 69 of the nation's 99
legislative chambers and 29 of the 50 governorships.
   More than 6,100 legislative races were decided across the
country, but the focus of national party organizations was about 50
races in 10 states in which chambers are held by narrow majorities.
   Even with California undecided, the Democrats were in position
to draw districts that in 1992 likely would pad their majority in
the House, now at 258-175, by a dozen seats or more beyond whatever
gains they made in Tuesday's elections.
   Preliminary census data suggest the remaining five House seats
that shift will go to Virginia, North Carolina, Georgia, Washington
and Arizona. Among those states, redistricting control was a
serious question only in Arizona. Democrats already had a
redistricting monopoly in Virginia and kept hold of their sole
control in North Carolina and Georgia. A nonpartisan commission
draws the map in Washington.
   Democrats were facing uphill odds in their effort to erase the
Arizona GOP's 17-13 Senate and 34-26 House majorities. But Democrat
Terry Goddard was leading in early returns in the governor's race .
If elected, he could veto any redistricting plan drawn by a
possibly Republican legislature.
   Among the 13 states losing seats, New York will suffer the most
- giving up three.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo was headed to easy re-election and the New York
Assembly had a 92-58 Democratic majority entering Tuesday's voting.
Results were slow to come in, but Democrats conceded they would not
capture the Senate, where they had hoped to wipe out a five-seat
Republican majority and gain a redistricting monopoly.
   Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan and Illinois are to lose two seats
each. Losing one will be Massachusetts, New Jersey, West Virginia,
Kentucky, Louisiana, Iowa, Kansas and Montana. Democrats control
the process in New Jersey, West Virginia, Kentucky and Louisiana.
In Massachusetts, Iowa, Kansas and Montana the power will be
shared.
