the party will try again to wrest control of the White House from
the GOP.
   Republicans for most of the 1980s touted their ``1991 Plan'' as
the means of escaping their nearly 40 years as minority party in
the House. But the GOP now finds itself scrambling to defend its
major redistricting power bases against formidable Democratic
challenges.
   Already, the GOP is threatening to press legal challenges to
partisan plans it expects the Democrats to craft.
   ``We're in position this year to successfully defend most if not
all of our redistricting strengths and then peel off a few if not
more from the Republicans,'' said Tim Dickson, executive director
of the Democratic Party's redistricting arm, Project 500.
   At stake is nothing less than control of the House through the
year 2003; even modest Democratic gains would cement Republicans as
the minority party for the foreseeable future.
   Party operatives say new computer analyses that mix Census
demographics with voting records will allow anyone with a monopoly
on redistricting to fashion no-lose districts.
   ``You can slice up a state and preordain the results with
incredible accuracy,'' said Ben Ginsberg, the Republican National
Committee's chief counsel.
   The Republicans hoped for big gains after 17 seats shifted from
the Frost Belt to the Sun Belt after the 1980 Census. But Democrats
controlled much of the map drawing and ended up with a net gain of
three seats.
   The shifting is called reapportionment, the Census Bureau term
for deciding how many of the 435 House seats go to each state. Once
that's done the states - in most cases their legislatures - take on
the task of redistricting, literally redrawing the lines of each
congressional district.
   There are 6,144 legislative seats up for election in 46 states.
There are no legislative races this year in Virginia, New Jersey,
Mississippi and Kentucky.
   After years of exhaustive research, the parties have narrowed
their targets to a handful to a dozen races in each of the major
redistricting battlegrounds - primarily states that are gaining or
losing seats.
   Fourteen of the shifting seats - and their accompanying
electoral votes in presidential elections - will be gobbled up by
California, Florida and Texas.
   In those states, Republicans now control the governor's office
but face stiff challenges this year.
   At the legislative level in those states, only control of the
Florida Senate appears in question; Democrats enjoy sizeable
advantages in both chambers of the Texas and California
legislatures and in the Florida House.
   Republicans are mounting an aggressive effort to pick up the
four seats they need to control the Florida Senate, which would
give the GOP a voice in redistricting should Republican Gov. Bob
Martinez lose his re-election bid.
   Democrats are cautiously optimistic they will retain their edge.
   The fight in the state destined to be the biggest redistricting
loser, New York, focuses on the state Senate, where Democrats need
a net gain of four seats to win a monopoly on redistricting.
   ``If that happens what you will see is blatant political
gerrymandering,'' said the RNC's Ginsberg.
   He won't get an argument from Democrats on that point.
   ``The process is inherently political,'' said Democratic
National Committee redistricting guru Mark Bohannon. ``It was
designed that way, to benefit winners.''
   President Bush has visited New York to help the GOP's state
Senate effort, and Gov. Mario Cuomo is working hard for the
Democrats. New York likely will lose three of its 34 House seats.
   Democrats also are spending heavily in hopes of gaining
redistricting monopolies in Pennsylvania, Indiana and Michigan.
They hope to capture the senates in Pennsylvania and Michigan and
both chambers in Indiana, where the GOP has two-seat majorities in
the House and Senate. With the Ohio gubernatorial contest leaning
Republican, Democrats also are targeting the Ohio Senate, where
they need a gain of three seats to win total control of the state
legislature.
   The party has realistic shots at those goals but faces uphill
odds in trying to erase slim GOP majorities in both chambers of the
Arizona legislature and the Colorado House.
   Democrats find themselves playing defense in the Florida Senate
contests as well as in Illinois, where Republicans need to gain two
seats to capture the Senate. Republicans also are trying to take
over the lower chambers in Pennsylvania and Oregon, needing a gain
of three seats in each state.
   The Pennsylvania, Michigan, Illinois and Ohio contests are
particularly important because each of these states is likely to
lose two congressional seats. Control over redistricting will
decide which incumbents get squeezed.
   The other likely losers are Massachusetts, New Jersey, West
Virginia, Kentucky, Iowa, Louisiana, Kansas and Montana. Those
eight states will lose one seat each, according to preliminary
Census data.
   The redistricting winners are led by California, which should
gain seven seats and see its House delegation grow to 52. Florida's
expected gain of four would bring its House delegation to 23. The
likely pickup of three seats by Texas would swell its
representation in the House to 30.
   Together, these states would supply 24 percent of House members
and hold 105 Electoral College votes - 38 percent of the 270 needed
to win the White House.
   The other gainers, expected to pick up one seat each, likely
will be Virginia, North Carolina, Georgia, Arizona and Washington.
   Heading into the elections there were just four states - Idaho,
Kansas, New Hampshire and South Dakota - in which Republicans have
outright control over state government and none of them are
considered major redistricting battlegrounds.
   Democrats, on the other hand, hold the governor's office and
control both legislative chambers in 15 states and at least two of
the three seats at the redistricting table in 23 others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

